T1  - Credit rationing and capital accumulation with investment and consumption loans revisited
AU  - Hung, Fu-Sheng
JO  - Journal of Development Economics
VL  - 78
IS  - 2
SP  - 322
EP  - 347
PY  - 2005
DA  - 2005/12/01/
SN  - 0304-3878
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jdeveco.2004.11.007
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0304387805000672
KW  - Asymmetric information
KW  - Credit rationing
KW  - Adverse selection
KW  - Development trap
AB  - A simple model is developed to evaluate the roles of credit rationing and government policies of financial repression in the process of capital accumulation. In the model, credit rationing on both investment and consumption loans decreases as capital accumulates but increases as the government imposes policies of financial repression to a greater extent. While a reduction in credit rationing on consumption loans impedes capital accumulation, such a reduction on investment loans facilitates it. We find that developing countries may be trapped at a low-capital-stock steady state while developed countries converge to a high-capital-stock steady state. Instead of adopting policies of financial liberalization, interestingly, this paper finds that policies of financial repression may enable developing countries to escape the development trap.
ER  - 

